items.title: Taking qualnames of builtins fails on Py2
items.body:
E.g.:

```

?  ~[regret:python] -c 'from qualname import qualname; print(qualname(str))'                                                                                          julian@Air ?
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<module>", line 1, in <module>
  File "/Users/julian/.local/share/virtualenvs/regret/site-packages/qualname.py", line 50, in qualname
    return obj.__qualname__  # raises a sensible error
AttributeError: type object 'str' has no attribute '__qualname__'
```

whereas `twisted.python.reflect.fullyQualifiedName` (which is what I'm comparing to :) produces the expected:

```

?  ~[regret:python] -c 'from twisted.python.reflect import fullyQualifiedName as qualname; print(qualname(str))'                                                      julian@Air ?
__builtin__.str
```

(other than the fact that qualname isn't fully qualified :()

items.title: Does not work as expected on Python 2.7.10
items.body:
Hi,

I have the same result both with the latest release of qualname and the git head :

```
Python 2.7.10 (default, Sep 11 2015, 16:20:58) 
[GCC 4.2.1 Compatible Apple LLVM 6.0 (clang-600.0.51)] on darwin
Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
>>> from qualname import qualname
>>> import sys
>>> qualname(sys.path)
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
  File "/Users/glenfant/.virtualenvs/tmp-7b11cc4070ee454c/lib/python2.7/site-packages/qualname.py", line 51, in qualname
    return obj.__qualname__  # raises a sensible error
AttributeError: 'list' object has no attribute '__qualname__'
>>> from sys import modules
>>> qualname(modules)
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
  File "/Users/glenfant/.virtualenvs/tmp-7b11cc4070ee454c/lib/python2.7/site-packages/qualname.py", line 51, in qualname
    return obj.__qualname__  # raises a sensible error
AttributeError: 'dict' object has no attribute '__qualname__'
```

Am I missing something or is it a bug ?
